  This contains the portable FORTRAN code for global and constrained
optimization as described in (1).
  Makefile to create library 'libgm.a' is for the unix systems, but it
can be easily modified for MS-DOS, or VMS. Additional compiler
optimization switches may be added for better performance.

  The files i1mach?.f contain machine dependent constants, and utility
functions.  The rest of the files implement optimization  methods.

Meaning of the constants that are in files i1mach?.f:

I1MACH(1) - stdin
I1MACH(2) - stdout
I1MACH(4) - stderr

I1MACH(5) - number of bits per integer
I1MACH(6) - number of bytes per integer

             Integers:
I1MACH(7) - is the base
I1MACH(8) - number of base digits
I1MACH(9) - the largest magnitude

             Floating Point Numbers:
I1MACH(10) - is the base
             
             Single Precision:
I1MACH(11) - is the number of base digits
I1MACH(12) - is the smallest exponent
I1MACH(13) - is the largest exponent

             Double Precision:
I1MACH(14) - is the number of base digits
I1MACH(15) - is the smallest exponent
I1MACH(16) - is the largest exponent

    Single Precision Machine Constants:
R1MACH(1) is the smallest positive magnitude
R1MACH(2) is the largest magnitude
R1MACH(3) is the smallest relative spacing 
R1MACH(4) is the largest  relative spacing 
R1MACH(5) LOG10(base)

    Double Precision Machine Constants:
D1MACH(1) is the smallest positive magnitude
D1MACH(2) is the largest magnitude
D1MACH(3) is the smallest relative spacing 
D1MACH(4) is the largest  relative spacing 
D1MACH(5) LOG10(base)



  
(1)  J. Mockus, Bayesian Approach to Global Optimization,
Kluwer Academic Publishers, Dordrecht-Boston-London, 1989.
ISBN 0-7923-0115-3, order: P.O.Box 322, 3300 AH Dordrecht,
The Netherlands.
